```python
import os

def delete_files(path):
    for root, directories, files in os.walk(path):
        for file in files:
            file_path = os.path.join(root, file)
            os.remove(file_path)
            print(f"Deleted file: {file_path}")

if __name__ == '__main__':
    # Path to the directory you want to delete all files
    directory = '/path/to/delete/face/bash_to/'

    # Call the function to delete all files in the specified directory
    delete_files(directory)
```

Make sure to replace '/path/to/delete/face/bash\_to/' with the appropriate path that matches your use case. When executed, this Python script will delete all files in the specified directory and display a message for each file that was deleted. If you want to delete files from the current working directory, just use an empty string rather than a specific path.
